<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1225]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,1025,1049]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is unique in the genus in having sensory head pores. Neither 
<bibRefCitation author="Myers" box="[1141,1294,1024,1049]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" refString="Myers, G. S. (1927) Descriptions of new South American fresh-water fishes collected by Dr. Carl Ternetz. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 68, 106 - 135." type="journal article" year="1927">
Myers (
<number box="[1227,1285,1024,1048]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" value="1927.0">1927</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
nor 
<bibRefCitation pageId="15" pageNumber="54" refString="Thacker, C. E., Pezold, F. L. &amp; Suttkus, R. D. (2006) Redescriptions on the dwarf Neotropical Eleotrid genus Leptophilypnus (Teleostei: Gobioidei), including a new species and comments on Microphilypnus. Copeia, 2006, 489 - 499." type="journal article">
Thacker 
<emphasis box="[151,207,1060,1084]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[221,280,1059,1083]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" value="2006.0">2006</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
paid much attention to the morphology of this system in 
<emphasis box="[924,1107,1060,1084]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">
<taxonomicName box="[924,1103,1060,1084]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Eleotridae" genus="Microphilypnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Microphilypnus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
although in the last paper the head sensory system of 
<taxonomicName box="[423,545,1096,1119]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Eleotridae" genus="Microphilypnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ternetzi">
<emphasis box="[423,545,1096,1119]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">M. ternetzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been represented (
<bibRefCitation author="Thacker" box="[804,1037,1095,1119]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" refString="Thacker, C. E., Pezold, F. L. &amp; Suttkus, R. D. (2006) Redescriptions on the dwarf Neotropical Eleotrid genus Leptophilypnus (Teleostei: Gobioidei), including a new species and comments on Microphilypnus. Copeia, 2006, 489 - 499." type="journal article" year="2006">
Thacker 
<emphasis box="[906,970,1095,1119]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">et al.,</emphasis>
<number box="[978,1037,1095,1119]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1049,1116,1095,1119]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1793,1816]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,807,1771]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,807,1771]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microphilypnus macrostoma. a) holotype, CAS 76820, Brazil: Amazonas, Manaus, igarapé da Mãe Joana, 15.5 mm SL. b) MZUSP 74234, Brazil: Amazonas, igarapé in Tapurucuara, 18.1 mm SL. c) INPA 26256, rio Negro basin, Igarapé Tarumã-Mirim, 17.0 mm SL. Photographs: CAS Dept. of Ichthyology (a) and R. A. Caires (b, c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201746/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">
Fig. 
<number box="[1101,1116,1095,1119]" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
D). In fact, we searched this feature in hundreds of specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[567,836,1130,1154]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Eleotridae" genus="Microphilypnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ternetzi">
<emphasis box="[567,836,1130,1154]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="54">Microphilypnus ternetzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but we were unable to see any external openings in the head canals of these individuals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
